WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.160
Hey everyone, my name is Cecil and I'm here with my colleague Jay and we're from the Posit

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:19.280
support team and today we're going to be talking a little bit about SSL certificates and SSL

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:20.680
certificate chains.

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:29.160
So just for some context, this is a host that we've created with Posit teams and there is

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:33.040
Workbench, Kinect, and Package Manager installed.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:40.959
Workbench has a CA-signed certificate, signed by Let's Encrypt, and Kinect has a self-signed

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:42.279
certificate.

00:00:42.279 --> 00:00:49.799
So there's a nifty command that uses the OpenSSL utility which will allow you to see if your

00:00:49.799 --> 00:00:53.160
certificate chain is complete or not.

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:59.799
So I've got that pre-prepared and I'll paste it in but effectively we use the OpenSSL command

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:05.160
and we paste in the URL of the host that we want to test.

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:11.040
In this case, we'll test Kinect which has the incomplete certificate.

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:16.720
So if we hit enter there, you'll notice that the verify return code is the most important

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:17.720
part.

00:01:18.279 --> 00:01:25.720
This should return a zero but as you see here, it returns an 18 because this is a self-signed

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:26.720
certificate.

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:31.879
So if we scroll up a little bit, we can see that there's only one certificate in this

00:01:31.879 --> 00:01:42.080
chain whereas with Workbench, if we were to run the same command for Workbench, you'll

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:49.720
notice that the verify return code is zero and it returns okay but there are more parts

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:53.199
to the SSL certificate chain.

00:01:53.199 --> 00:02:02.720
So this is a Let's Encrypt certificate that typically you don't share your specific certificate

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:03.720
like this.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:08.960
This host will be deleted after this video but typically what it looks like is you'll

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:16.839
see either two or three different parts of the certificate to the chain and in most cases

00:02:16.839 --> 00:02:21.320
they should be concatenated into the single file.

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:27.080
As long as you're running this command and seeing the return okay, in most cases you

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:30.080
know your certificate file is set up well.

